1
00:00:00,188 --> 00:00:04,645
AI DevKit is an operating model for AI-centric software engineering.

2
00:00:05,950 --> 00:00:09,766
AI writes specs, tests, code, and docs.

3
00:00:10,910 --> 00:00:13,368
Humans approve the spec and approve the release.

4
00:00:14,473 --> 00:00:16,963
It works with your existing stack — git,

5
00:00:17,109 --> 00:00:22,402
repos, pull requests, continuous integration — and reshapes it around AI

6
00:00:22,474 --> 00:00:26,009
execution, while keeping the human checkpoints that matter.

7
00:00:27,277 --> 00:00:29,603
There are four pillars: spec planning,

8
00:00:29,731 --> 00:00:35,033
test-driven implementation, progressive disclosure docs, and the AI dev

9
00:00:35,106 --> 00:00:35,990
environment.

10
00:00:36,192 --> 00:00:37,672
Work comes in as a story,

11
00:00:37,768 --> 00:00:39,753
epic, bug, or feature.

12
00:00:41,018 --> 00:00:43,911
It flows through three phases: Plan,

13
00:00:43,954 --> 00:00:45,757
Implementation, and Release.

14
00:00:46,776 --> 00:00:49,195
The Lead AI executes the workflow.

15
00:00:50,778 --> 00:00:51,832
The Verify A.I.

16
00:00:51,896 --> 00:00:56,956
independently reviews all Lead AI work — it's a second AI

17
00:00:57,004 --> 00:00:58,873
from a different training lineage.

18
00:01:00,296 --> 00:01:01,435
Why two AIs?

19
00:01:02,832 --> 00:01:07,635
A single AI is confidently wrong in ways invisible to itself.

20
00:01:08,631 --> 00:01:12,632
Asking the same model to review its own output rarely catches the

21
00:01:12,685 --> 00:01:13,030
error.

22
00:01:14,609 --> 00:01:17,835
Two independent lineages catch different mistakes.

23
00:01:19,414 --> 00:01:21,355
The Plan phase produces a spec.

24
00:01:23,123 --> 00:01:25,754
The Implementation phase produces working code,

25
00:01:25,847 --> 00:01:27,992
tests, and updated docs.

26
00:01:29,242 --> 00:01:34,795
That deliverable passes through Release — continuous integration and delivery pipelines

27
00:01:34,955 --> 00:01:36,635
plus human approval.

28
00:01:36,903 --> 00:01:39,832
Plan turns a work item into an approved spec.

29
00:01:41,412 --> 00:01:43,430
The Lead AI reads the requirement,

30
00:01:43,450 --> 00:01:48,151
the docs, and the code, then drafts a spec with acceptance criteria,

31
00:01:48,199 --> 00:01:50,308
edge cases, and approach decisions.

32
00:01:52,207 --> 00:01:53,344
The Verify A.I.

33
00:01:53,415 --> 00:01:55,427
reviews the spec independently.

34
00:01:56,692 --> 00:02:00,786
If the two AIs disagree on what a criterion means,

35
00:02:00,854 --> 00:02:04,384
that's ambiguity — and it gets surfaced to the human before any

36
00:02:04,448 --> 00:02:05,343
code is written.

37
00:02:07,011 --> 00:02:10,215
The key discipline here: decide in the spec,

38
00:02:10,295 --> 00:02:11,335
not in the code.

39
00:02:12,436 --> 00:02:16,143
If you let the AI defer decisions to implementation,

40
00:02:16,288 --> 00:02:19,735
it makes them implicitly, often inconsistently,

41
00:02:19,867 --> 00:02:22,132
and you only find out when you're reading the code.

42
00:02:24,031 --> 00:02:26,532
The phase ends when the human signs off.

43
00:02:27,313 --> 00:02:30,852
Implementation turns the approved spec into working code.

44
00:02:32,671 --> 00:02:33,812
The Verify A.I.

45
00:02:33,902 --> 00:02:37,736
authors the failing tests directly from the spec.

46
00:02:39,639 --> 00:02:44,574
The Lead AI writes the implementation to make them pass.

47
00:02:45,712 --> 00:02:51,018
This is independent test authorship — the AI that writes the tests

48
00:02:51,177 --> 00:02:54,856
is not the AI that writes the code.

49
00:02:55,882 --> 00:03:01,250
Without that separation, implementation assumptions get silently baked into

50
00:03:01,270 --> 00:03:02,970
the tests.

51
00:03:04,120 --> 00:03:09,658
After test-driven development completes, the Lead AI updates the progressive disclosure

52
00:03:09,754 --> 00:03:12,379
docs, and the Verify A.I.

53
00:03:12,494 --> 00:03:15,658
checks the updates against the actual code.

54
00:03:17,322 --> 00:03:19,096
Then the spec is archived.

55
00:03:19,799 --> 00:03:22,132
The docs carry everything forward.

56
00:03:22,587 --> 00:03:26,599
Progressive Disclosure docs give every repo the same structure.

57
00:03:28,348 --> 00:03:31,236
The same eight files, in every repo,

58
00:03:31,328 --> 00:03:33,556
across the whole organisation.

59
00:03:35,569 --> 00:03:39,233
Level zero is an identity card — what is this repo?

60
00:03:41,042 --> 00:03:43,879
Level one is eight fixed files:

61
00:03:45,237 --> 00:03:51,314
setup, architecture, code map, conventions, workflows,

62
00:03:51,388 --> 00:03:54,356
interfaces, gotchas, and security.

63
00:03:56,370 --> 00:04:01,555
Level two is deep dives, loaded only when Level one isn't enough.

64
00:04:02,721 --> 00:04:07,478
Levels zero and one load upfront — they're small.

65
00:04:08,867 --> 00:04:11,401
Level two is pulled in only when needed.

66
00:04:12,903 --> 00:04:17,084
The agent gets full context without filling the context window.

67
00:04:18,982 --> 00:04:23,725
That consistency is what lets any agent pick up any repo and

68
00:04:23,788 --> 00:04:24,687
work safely.

69
00:04:24,955 --> 00:04:28,524
Real systems span multiple repos — an API,

70
00:04:28,576 --> 00:04:32,036
an SDK, a frontend, shared infrastructure.

71
00:04:33,615 --> 00:04:38,034
The AI dev environment gives you one workspace where the AI can

72
00:04:38,074 --> 00:04:40,195
run the whole system end to end.

73
00:04:41,456 --> 00:04:43,389
It's a container of containers.

74
00:04:44,781 --> 00:04:47,707
Each component runs in its own container,

75
00:04:47,983 --> 00:04:51,346
all inside one outer workspace.

76
00:04:52,324 --> 00:04:55,223
The Lead AI can start, stop,

77
00:04:55,303 --> 00:04:58,341
restart, and test any component from there.

78
00:04:59,587 --> 00:05:02,382
It runs locally or in the cloud.

79
00:05:03,392 --> 00:05:08,100
Cloud workspaces are useful for team handoff — another engineer picks up

80
00:05:08,161 --> 00:05:11,700
the same workspace and the same context.

81
00:05:12,560 --> 00:05:17,697
The environment includes Playwright for browser testing and Terraform for infrastructure.

82
00:05:18,987 --> 00:05:24,344
And there's an audit trail across all agent sessions — reproducibility,

83
00:05:24,397 --> 00:05:28,423
traceability, and evals for debugging agent behaviour.

84
00:05:28,750 --> 00:05:32,658
Everything in AI DevKit runs through six markdown files in a prompts

85
00:05:32,714 --> 00:05:33,137
folder.

86
00:05:33,951 --> 00:05:37,451
spec, implement, create docs, update docs,

87
00:05:37,531 --> 00:05:40,252
verify with Codex, verify with Claude.

88
00:05:40,629 --> 00:05:42,649
They're plain text — you can read them,

89
00:05:42,699 --> 00:05:45,612
understand exactly what the AI is being told to do,

90
00:05:45,672 --> 00:05:46,654
and modify them.

91
00:05:46,961 --> 00:05:49,492
Why not skills or slash commands?

92
00:05:49,673 --> 00:05:52,566
There are lots of ways to load instructions into an AI tool

93
00:05:52,646 --> 00:05:56,406
— user settings, project files, enterprise configs,

94
00:05:56,497 --> 00:05:58,442
skills, slash commands.

95
00:05:58,627 --> 00:05:59,961
It's a walled garden.

96
00:06:00,360 --> 00:06:02,233
A Claude skill doesn't work in Cursor.

97
00:06:02,382 --> 00:06:04,867
A Cursor command doesn't work in Codex.

98
00:06:05,007 --> 00:06:05,990
But at the end of the day,

99
00:06:06,043 --> 00:06:08,149
it's all just text hitting an LLM.

100
00:06:08,428 --> 00:06:11,268
Prompts are portable — you can paste them into any agent,

101
00:06:11,321 --> 00:06:13,146
or pipe them from the command line.

102
00:06:13,459 --> 00:06:16,826
Curl the prompts straight from GitHub — no clone needed.

103
00:06:17,005 --> 00:06:20,465
For example: curl create-docs and verify-codex,

104
00:06:20,528 --> 00:06:21,625
pipe to claude.

105
00:06:21,810 --> 00:06:24,865
Or flip it — curl create-docs and verify-claude,

106
00:06:24,946 --> 00:06:26,067
pass to codex.

107
00:06:26,317 --> 00:06:31,832
Either way, one command generates Progressive Disclosure docs and runs cross-model verification

108
00:06:31,872 --> 00:06:34,228
— end to end, about fifty minutes,

109
00:06:34,308 --> 00:06:35,944
zero human intervention.

110
00:06:36,420 --> 00:06:38,101
Visible prompts are accountable.

111
00:06:38,130 --> 00:06:40,379
Hidden skills may or may not be followed.

112
00:06:40,971 --> 00:06:44,384
Engineers should read the prompts, not trust hidden instructions.

113
00:06:44,450 --> 00:06:46,259
Here's how to start.

114
00:06:47,218 --> 00:06:48,223
Pick one repo.

115
00:06:49,997 --> 00:06:54,622
Curl create-docs, pipe to claude — or pass to codex.

116
00:06:56,271 --> 00:06:59,980
That's it — any agent can then pick up that repo and

117
00:07:00,028 --> 00:07:01,504
work safely.

118
00:07:02,593 --> 00:07:07,829
Chain verify-codex or verify-claude for cross-model review —

119
00:07:07,882 --> 00:07:09,189
works in either direction.

120
00:07:10,528 --> 00:07:22,954
The repo, the standard, and all the prompts are open at github.com/AgoraIO-Community/ai-devkit.

